Regression Project: Boston House Price Prediction¶

Marks: 60¶

Welcome to the project on regression. We will use the Boston house price dataset for this project.

Objective¶

The problem at hand is to predict the housing prices of a town or a suburb based on the features of the locality provided to us. In the process, we need to identify the most important features affecting the price of the house. We need to employ techniques of data preprocessing and build a linear regression model that predicts the prices for the unseen data.

Dataset¶

Each record in the database describes a house in Boston suburb or town. The data was drawn from the Boston Standard Metropolitan Statistical Area (SMSA) in 1970. Detailed attribute information can be found below:

Attribute Information:

  • CRIM: Per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN: Proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS: Proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX: Nitric Oxide concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM: The average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE: Proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940
  • DIS: Weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
  • RAD: Index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX: Full-value property-tax rate per 10,000 dollars
  • PTRATIO: Pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • LSTAT: % lower status of the population
  • MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in 1000 dollars

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of 'MEDV' look like?
  2. What can we infer form the correlation heatmap? Is there correlation between the dependent and independent variables?
  3. What are all the inferences that can be found by doing univariate analysis for different variables?
  4. Do bivariate analysis to visualize the relationship between the features having significant correlations (>= 0.7 or <= -0.7)

Answers:

  1. The distribution of 'MEDV' looks to be right skewed with a very large set of outliers in the range of 48 to 50.
  2. The CHAS (Charles River dummy variable) has seemingly no correlation to any other variable, while others, like DIS (weighted distances to five Boston employment centers), have some high correlations with other variables like NOX, AGE, and INDUS. A large majority do not have strong correlations.
  3. CRIM, ZN, CHAS, NOX, DIS, RAD, LSTAT, MEDV: Most of the values are low; INDUS, TAX: Most values are either low or high; RM: Values are almost evenly distributed; AGE, PTRATIO: Most values are high.
  4. Graphs found below. As INDUS increases, NOX goes down (negative correlation). As DIS increases, NOX goes down (negative correlation). As AGE increases, NOX goes up (positive correlation). As AGE increases, DIS goes down (negative correlation).

Model Performance Check¶

  1. How does the model is performing? Check using Rsquared, RSME, MAE, MAPE
  2. Is there multicollinearity? Check using VIF
  3. How does the model is performing after cross validation?
  1. As seen in the values below, the model is performing relatively well. R-squared is relatively high (0.772) and the RSME, MAE, and MAPE values are all quite low (0.188, 0.126, 4.457%). This means that the model explains 77.2% of the variance in the taget variable, with a 0.188 average error (or 4.457%) and a 0.126 average absolute difference between predicted and actual values. With that said, the model has room for improvement.
  2. There is multicollinearity present due to the presence of a very high Condition Number, but this is not evident in the VIF number. Especially after dropping the TAX and NOX columns which had high VIF numbers, all numbers are low enough for there to be mutlicollinearity.
  3. After cross validation, the model performs slightly better than previously, mostly by drastically lowering the RSME score, while only slightly increasing the R-squared.
In [47]:
#vif function
def vif_func(train):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = train.columns

    vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(train.values, i) for i in range(len(train.columns))]
    return vif

print(vif_func(independent_train))

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.

Checking for mean residuals¶

In [57]:
# Getting predictions for the purpose of residuals
predictions = lin_model.fit(independent_train, dependent_train).predict(independent_train)
residuals = dependent_train - predictions

mean_residuals = np.mean(residuals)

print("Mean of Residuals:", mean_residuals)

Mean of Residuals: -3.8747882790135414e-16

Observations¶

  • Although not 0, it is a number so small (multiplied by 10 to the power of -16) that it is practically 0.

Checking for homoscedasticity¶

In [58]:
from statsmodels.stats.diagnostic import het_white
from statsmodels.compat import lzip
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms

name = ['F statistic', 'p-value']
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(residuals, independent_train)
print(dict(zip(name, test)))

{'F statistic': 1.0134247518499377, 'p-value': 0.46333756437056045}

Observations¶

  • Due to the P-Value being over 0.05, then the residuals are heteroscedastic

Linearity of variables¶

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Meaningful Insights:

  • Due to checks for Mean Residuals, Homoscedasticity, and Linearity of variables giving a seemingly incorrect assessment of the data's linearity, it is worth considering that linear regression might not be the best relationship for this data, even though the predicted values match pretty well to the actual dependent test values, and the R-squared and RMSE have good values.
  • The final model being the one that removes factors such as TAX and NOX being the omre appropriate answer in comparison to a general linear regression that considers all values means that there are variables that are not important in the decision of house prices. This also could lead to the reality that removing more columns of variables might lead to a better relationship.
  • With that said, whenever TAX and NOX were removed from the model, the R-squared and RMSE scores worsened instead of improving, while the VIF values improved to an acceptable level, which is why no more columns were removed. If more columns are removed, the R-squared and RMSE scores worsen significantly while the VIF values didn't improve by much.
  • This could mean that there are more variables to predicting housing prices that are not being taken into account in the information provided by the database.

Recommendations:

  • Further tuning done in model, as well as testing relationships other than linear regression, such as Ridge/Lasso Regression or Decision Trees, is needed in order to fin the truly best option for this project. Although linear regression does show a good relationship and the R-squared and RMSE have good values, they could be better, and other models could fit the data better as well.
  • The housing market rapidly changes nowadays, especially with the increasingly higher prices present in cities. The model might need to be retrained somewhat frequently to account for the rapid growth of certain cities (like recently Dallas, Texas) or the preferences of renting over purchasing.
  • Similarly, this is just a general database of prices and its economic factors like Taxes or intrinsic details of the home like its Age. This leaves out other factors surrounding the home, such as if it was remodeled, if it is in a large city, etc. that heavily impact house pricing.
  • Certain markets, like California or New York, might have extremely expensive outliers that do not follow the same relationship as the general market, while some poor, rural areas with really bad housing markets might suffer from similar issues, so if a general model that will be applied to everything is created, it should be done with discretion as it might miss those nuances.
